las</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Erskine Of Kinnoul was born about 1344, in Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Robert Erskine, was 35 and his mother, Lady Beatrice de Lindsay, was 60. He had at least 1 daughter with Jean Cameron. He died in 1406, in Kinnoull, Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1344–Bef. 1406":"umbes 1344–1406","1328–1346":"1328–1346","1338–1406":"1338–1406","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1344–1406":"1344–1406","1346–1403":"1346–1403","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1356–1402":"1356–1402","1385–1452":"1385–1452","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1285–1352":"1285–1352","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1285":"1285","1349":"1349","1338":"1338","Bef. 1406":"1406","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1346":"1346","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1452":"1452","1342":"1342","2 May 1352":"2. mai 1352","about 1344":"umbes 1344","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","Angus, Scotland":"Scotland","Kinnoull, Perthshire, Scotland":"Kinnoull, Perthshire, Scotland","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1344–Bef. 1406":"noin 1344–1406","1328–1346":"1328–1346","1338–1406":"1338–1406","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1344–1406":"1344–1406","1346–1403":